LAN rules 

outbound access: action is set to Pass to allow all LAN devices to reach the internet through pfSense WAN, we specify both TCP/UDP protocols, for source we specify the whole LAN subnet - for destination we specify any and as for source + destination port we specify any	
agent traffic to Zabbix: action is set to Pass, we specify TCP as protocol,	for source we specify the whole LAN subnet - for destination we specify the IP of zabbix which is	172.16.X.X	and for destination port we specify the 10050
ping to Zabbix server: action is set to Pass, we specify the ICMP protocol, as source w especify the whole LAN subnet - for destination we specify the IP	of zabbix which is 172.16.X.X  and as for destination port we specify any

- explanation:

Without LAN-out rule, LAN devices have no outbound internet access. pfSense stateful tracking automatically allows return traffic without a separate WAN rule.
In agent traffic to zabbix rule the port 10050 is the Zabbix agent passive check port. Zabbix server connects to the agent on this port to pull metrics
ICMP-zabbix allows the Linux VM to ping the Zabbix server. Required for ping-based monitoring and basic connectivity testing between zones

DMZ interface rules

outbound access: action is set to Pass, as protocol we specify IPv4 Any, for source we specify the whole subnet	 172.16.X.0/24 - for destination we specify any and for the destination port we speicfy the any	
SNMP — Zabbix queries pfSense: action is set to Pass,as protocol we specify the	UDP, for source we specify the IP of zabbix which is 	172.16.X.X - for destination we specify the DMZ IP which is 172.16.X.X, for destination port we specify the SNMP port which is the 161

- explanation: 

outbound access -> allows the Zabbix server to reach the internet, required for downloading packages, NTP sync, and monitoring 8.8.8.8 as an internet health check. Without this rule, DMZ is completely isolated (pfSense default deny).
SNMP rule -> allows only the Zabbix server IP to query pfSense on UDP 161. Scoping to a single source IP is intentional because SNMP should never be open to the entire DMZ subnet.

WAN interface rules

Pi-to-Zabbix (auto from port forward): action is set to Pass,	TCP protocol, for source is the IP of Pi which is the	192.168.X.X - for destination is the IP	WAN address	and for destination port we specify again  the port of zabbix which is the 10050 

Note: pfSense blocks all unsolicited inbound traffic by default — no explicit deny rule is needed. WAN rules only need to be created when we want to allow specific inbound traffic. 
The Pi rule was auto-generated by the port forward configuration and should not be manually recreated separately.

Outbound NAT rules

Auto-generated by pfSense: for exiting interface we have the WAN, for source we have the whole LAN subnet, for destination IP we have the WAN interface address	
NAT DMZ to WAN — manually added: for exiting interface we have again the WAN,	for source we have the whole DMZ subnet, for destination IP we have theWAN interface address	

Why the DMZ NAT rule must be manual

In NAT rules we specify the pfSense in Hybrid outbound NAT mode because automatically creates NAT rules for interfaces configured during initial setup (typically LAN). The DMZ interface was added later and was not automatically included in the outbound NAT ruleset.
Without this rule, DMZ traffic exits through WAN with a private source IP that the internet cannot route replies back to.

Port forward rules

Pi agent traffic to Zabbix: for incoming interface we use the WAN because it tells pfSense to listen for incoming packets trying to access our IP from the outside, for protocol we use	TCP, for destination we use the WAN address, for destination port we use the 10050, for redirect target we use the zabbix-server IP 172.16.10.15	that should receive the traffic and we specify the port of zabbix which is the 10050	

 - explanation:
The Raspberry Pi on the home LAN needs to reach the Zabbix server on DMZ. The Pi can only address packets to IPs it knows about, it knows pfSense's WAN IP but has no knowledge of the private DMZ subnet. 
The port forward intercepts packets arriving at pfSense WAN on port 10050 and rewrites the destination to 172.16.X.X:10050 (zabbix-server) before firewall rules are evaluated. pfSense then routes the rewritten packet into the DMZ. Without the port forward, pfSense accepts the packet at its WAN IP and has no instruction to forward it further.
